HOW TO USE COGNOS_REPORT_TESTER TO PARSE AND CHECK VALIDITY OF COGNOS REPORTS

1. If you don't have git, download and install git from the internet.

2. Open VSCode (or an equivalent IDE) and open a new window. 

3. Click "Open Folder..." and make a new folder/directory wherever you want the scripts to be stored. Select that folder.

4. Click the menu button in VSCode > View > Terminal

5. Enter into the terminal: git clone https://github.com/LargoLardo/cognos_report_tester.git

6. You should now see all of the scripts and misc appear in your directory/sidebar. Now, we need to create a venv to store all our dependencies. To do so, enter: python -m venv venv

7. Activate the venv for Windows by entering: venv\Scripts\activate.bat

8. To automatically install all dependencies, enter into the terminal: pip install requirements.txt

9. In your directory/sidebar, create a new file called: .env

10. It should be just ".env". Next, copy and paste the contents of example_env.txt in to the .env file. Press ctrl+s to save the file. If needed, change the urls and paths if working with and validating the reports of a different environment. By default, this file has the urls and paths for the dev environment.

11. Now we can actually begin using the scripts for recording and validation. The order of usage should be create_auth_state.py > url_recorder.py > report_validator.py. rest_api.py is just a helper file.

12. Enter into the terminal: python create_auth_state.py

13. Log in using PKI or external log in methods

14. Enter into the terminal: python url_recorder.py. Log in and wait until it finishes.

15. Enter into the terminal: python report_validator.py. By default, the number of parallel workers is 10 to speed up the process, wait until it finishes.

